<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-04-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-04-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="253" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d253">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/1865</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the High Commissioner in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Russell</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-04-01"><hi rend="italic">April 1,
                                1926</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 298</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department encloses, for your
                            information, a copy of its note of March 26, 1926, to the French
                                Embassy<note n="45" xml:id="d253fn45"><hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note> relating to the desire of the French Government
                            that the United States make representations to the Government of Haiti
                            with a view to inducing the latter to agree to submit to arbitration the
                            question whether the Haitian five per cent loan of 1910 is payable in
                            gold francs or in francs of current circulation.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Robert
                                    E. Olds</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>